SIMPLE: shroud
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shroud
<hw>Shroud</hw> <pr>(shroud)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>shroud</ets>, <ets>shrud</ets>, <ets>schrud</ets>, AS.
<ets>scr⟦umac⟧d</ets> a garment, clothing; akin to Icel.
<ets>skru⟦edh⟧</ets> the shrouds of a ship, furniture of a church, a
kind of stuff, Sw. <ets>skrud</ets> dress, attire, and E.
<ets>shred</ets>. See <er>Shred</er>, and cf. <er>Shrood</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>That which clothes, covers, conceals, or protects; a
garment.</def> <rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Swaddled, as new born, in sable <qex>shrouds</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Especially, the dress for the dead; a winding
sheet.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A dead man in his <xex>shroud</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which covers or shelters like a
shroud.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jura answers through her misty <qex>shroud</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A covered place used as a retreat or shelter, as a
cave or den; also, a vault or crypt.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>shroud</qex> to which he won⟦br⟧
His fair-eyed oxen.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A vault, or <qex>shroud</qex>, as under a church.</q>
<rj><qau>Withals.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The branching top of a tree; foliage.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Assyrian wad a cedar in Lebanon, with fair branches and with a
shadowing <qex>shroad</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ezek. xxxi. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A set of ropes
serving as stays to support the masts. The lower shrouds are secured to
the sides of vessels by heavy iron bolts and are passed around the head
of the lower masts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>One of the two annular plates at
the periphery of a water wheel, which form the sides of the buckets; a
shroud plate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bowsprit shrouds</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>ropes
extending from the head of the bowsprit to the sides of the vessel.</cd>
-- <col><b>Futtock shrouds</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>iron rods
connecting the topmast rigging with the lower rigging, passing over the
edge of the top.</cd> -- <col><b>Shroud plate</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>An iron plate extending from the dead-eyes to the
ship's side</cd>. <au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Mach.)</fld> <cd>A shroud. See def. 7, above.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shroud</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shroud
<hw>Shroud</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shrouded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shrouding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>scr<?/dan</ets>.
See <er>Shroud</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover with
a shroud; especially, to inclose in a winding sheet; to dress for the
grave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ancient Egyptian mummies were <qex>shrouded</qex> in a number
of folds of linen besmeared with gums.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cover, as with a shroud; to protect completely;
to cover so as to conceal; to hide; to veil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One of these trees, with all his young ones, may <qex>shroud</qex>
four hundred horsemen.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some tempest rise,⟦br⟧
And blow out all the stars that light the skies,⟦br⟧
To <qex>shroud</qex> my shame.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shroud</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shroud
<hw>Shroud</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To take shelter or harbor.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If your stray attendance be yet lodged,⟦br⟧
Or <qex>shroud</qex> within these limits.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shroud</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Shroud
<hw>Shroud</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To lop. See
<er>Shrood</er>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shrouded</ent>⟦br⟧
